WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.000
Thank you, yeah, this is a new package, it's only been released last December, made public.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:16.280
We've actually been working on it since March.

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:22.360
It's not just me, it's going to be also Barrett, who's over there, and George Heng, huge contributions

00:00:22.360 --> 00:00:24.480
from them to make this possible.

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:31.639
So this is my name, making gt is my game apparently, and I'm available on Twitter, email, GitHub,

00:00:31.639 --> 00:00:34.680
all the places.

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:40.720
So the gt package lets you build display tables with easy-to-use functions.

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:41.720
Now the key was easy.

00:00:41.720 --> 00:00:48.560
We wanted to make these functions easy to use and fall into a pit of success, really.

00:00:48.959 --> 00:00:54.680
They can be HTML, LaTeX, that's how I pronounce that, and RTF.

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:59.080
Now the first time I saw RTF, it was a real WTF.

00:00:59.080 --> 00:01:07.320
So I'm hoping you never have to do that yourself, generate RTF code, it's actually just hell.

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:08.320
So the package is available on GitHub.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:14.440
It's going to be a while until we get it on CRAN, we just really want to get the internals

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:16.160
right.

00:01:16.160 --> 00:01:21.239
So the basic workflow is you've got a table data, this can be a table or a data frame,

00:01:21.239 --> 00:01:25.419
and you introduce the gt, and it becomes a gt object, and you can use all the functions

00:01:25.419 --> 00:01:26.419
inside gt.

00:01:26.419 --> 00:01:29.559
There's lots to modify the table.

00:01:29.559 --> 00:01:33.400
What you get in the end is a gt table, and that, again, is HTML, LaTeX, or RTF.

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:38.559
That can be done in R Markdown, it can be done in the console, wherever.

00:01:38.559 --> 00:01:39.559
Okay.

00:01:39.559 --> 00:01:43.879
When we first set out to make this package, we thought, what are some useful features

00:01:43.879 --> 00:01:44.879
in display tables?

00:01:44.879 --> 00:01:48.879
What do we bring into the table, as it were?

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:52.400
First thing is kind of obvious, a table header, it's nice to have a title and a subtitle.

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:53.400
It's fantastic.

00:01:53.400 --> 00:01:57.000
It sort of identifies the table, describes it.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:58.000
We had to have that.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:01:59.000
So we put that in.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:00.480
Row labels.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:01.480
So here's a cool thing.

00:02:01.480 --> 00:02:05.360
We've got cars, and we have these countries where the cars came from.

00:02:05.360 --> 00:02:08.600
So we basically have groups of rows, we'll call them row groups.

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:11.479
So it allows you to sort of structure your rows, essentially.

00:02:11.479 --> 00:02:13.020
It's quite nice.

00:02:13.059 --> 00:02:14.059
This is probably a bit more familiar.

00:02:14.059 --> 00:02:18.660
It's column labels, just having column spanners over certain columns.

00:02:18.660 --> 00:02:24.779
So here we can see performance going over top of, you know, a few other columns.

00:02:24.779 --> 00:02:26.139
A really big thing is data formatting.

00:02:26.139 --> 00:02:32.779
We want to make it super easy to have your data transformed to any way you want.

00:02:32.779 --> 00:02:33.899
This is actually a gt table.

00:02:33.899 --> 00:02:36.699
So as you can see here, the data, of course, doesn't come in this way.

00:02:36.699 --> 00:02:40.699
You format yourself, and there's easy ways to target different cells and to make the

00:02:40.699 --> 00:02:43.419
formatting easy.

00:02:43.419 --> 00:02:44.419
And this was a big one.

00:02:44.419 --> 00:02:45.419
Footnotes.

00:02:45.419 --> 00:02:46.419
I love footnotes.

00:02:46.419 --> 00:02:49.979
The idea you can put little notes, you can annotate your table.

00:02:49.979 --> 00:02:54.619
A real nightmare sometimes when making a table is, like, getting them in the right order.

00:02:54.619 --> 00:02:57.059
So gt always puts them in the right order.

00:02:57.059 --> 00:03:00.339
We don't have to worry what order you specify the footnotes.

00:03:00.339 --> 00:03:01.779
Gt will handle it.

00:03:01.779 --> 00:03:04.940
So you can see right here, footnotes are kind of small to see, so I called them out.

00:03:04.940 --> 00:03:07.699
It's always going to be left to right, top down in terms of numbering.

00:03:07.699 --> 00:03:11.339
And you can see the notes at the bottom, they're also in order.

00:03:11.339 --> 00:03:15.820
So you don't have to worry about order when you're doing footnotes in gt.

00:03:15.820 --> 00:03:21.139
So in order to make this work really well, we need to define a structure for a table.

00:03:21.139 --> 00:03:24.520
Some sort of, like, structure that will solve 90% of your table needs.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:27.460
So we call them table parts.

00:03:27.460 --> 00:03:29.539
So the most basic table is this.

00:03:29.539 --> 00:03:30.539
It's very familiar.

00:03:30.539 --> 00:03:31.539
You've got column labels.

00:03:31.539 --> 00:03:32.539
You've got a table body.

00:03:32.539 --> 00:03:33.539
The table body has cells.

00:03:33.539 --> 00:03:36.100
It's arranged in columns and rows.

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:37.100
Very, very familiar.

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:39.179
It's the most basic form of table.

00:03:39.179 --> 00:03:40.539
But here's a cool thing.

00:03:40.539 --> 00:03:42.740
A stub.

00:03:42.740 --> 00:03:46.619
It's a little known term in table technology.

00:03:46.619 --> 00:03:47.619
It's essentially like row names.

00:03:47.619 --> 00:03:50.220
But we can do better than row names, like in data frames.

00:03:50.220 --> 00:03:54.460
We can have a stub that defines, we can have labels for each row.

00:03:54.460 --> 00:03:58.860
Again, it's not always needed, but it can be useful in certain circumstances.

00:03:58.860 --> 00:04:04.779
Like if rows are representing some sort of thing that you want to call out.

00:04:04.779 --> 00:04:07.820
And because we can conceivably have groups of rows, it's nice.

00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:12.539
We can have space there for a row group label that extends out into the table body, which

00:04:12.539 --> 00:04:15.020
is really quite nice.

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:18.500
And a feature of GT is creating summary rows.

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:20.839
So if you have summary rows, you can have summary labels.

00:04:20.839 --> 00:04:23.739
You can identify what are in the summary cells.

00:04:23.739 --> 00:04:26.100
It can be, like, an average, a range, what have you.

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:27.420
It's nice to describe what that is.

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:30.420
Otherwise you wouldn't really know.

00:04:30.420 --> 00:04:31.859
So at the top, we have a table header.

00:04:32.179 --> 00:04:34.980
It's a great place to add a title and a subtitle.

00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:37.100
The best place, really.

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:38.980
And the bottom is the footer area.

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:43.019
That's where you throw in the footnotes, as many as you want, and source notes.

00:04:43.019 --> 00:04:45.619
So it's like a special type of note that just...

00:04:45.619 --> 00:04:49.459
You can use it for all sorts of things, but typically use it to just, you know, say the

00:04:49.459 --> 00:04:51.140
source of the data or other things.

00:04:51.140 --> 00:04:53.339
Other little notes that are not really labeled.

00:04:53.339 --> 00:04:54.339
Okay.

00:04:54.339 --> 00:05:00.619
So a question you might be asking is, do we have the functions to get these display tables

00:05:00.619 --> 00:05:01.619
made?

00:05:01.619 --> 00:05:02.619
Yes.

00:05:02.619 --> 00:05:03.619
We totally do.

00:05:03.619 --> 00:05:04.619
We have lots of functions.

00:05:04.619 --> 00:05:07.619
That's why it took so long to get this package out.

00:05:07.619 --> 00:05:10.140
We were just writing functions like crazy.

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:11.700
So the main one is GT.

00:05:11.700 --> 00:05:14.220
That's how you introduce your table data to GT.

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:15.220
So it's great.

00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:16.220
You have table data.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:17.540
Again, table or data frame.

00:05:17.540 --> 00:05:20.019
Just pipe that into GT, and you got that object.

00:05:20.019 --> 00:05:21.940
And just right there, it looks pretty good.

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:23.140
I'll show you some demos.

00:05:23.140 --> 00:05:24.140
The second...

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:28.820
The back half of this talk is like a live coding situation inside RStudio, which is

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:33.380
always risky, but I like to live dangerously.

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:34.380
So yeah.

00:05:34.380 --> 00:05:36.940
It may be the case where your table data is huge.

00:05:36.940 --> 00:05:39.299
It's not really summarized.

00:05:39.299 --> 00:05:42.059
But luckily we have tools like tidyverse.

00:05:42.059 --> 00:05:46.899
We can summarize our data, do cool things to it, reshape it.

00:05:46.899 --> 00:05:53.140
And then when it's ready, then you bring it to GT for the final touches, as it were.

00:05:53.140 --> 00:05:54.820
So we have lots of families of functions.

00:05:54.820 --> 00:05:57.880
I'm going to just introduce you to two families.

00:05:57.880 --> 00:06:00.200
We have these tab underscore functions.

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:04.000
And these are just concerned with adding parts to a table.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.640
So they're all targeting a different element.

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:10.200
So a tab header is routing a table header.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:12.260
Spanner is routing spanner columns.

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:13.799
And tab footnote is routing footnotes.

00:06:13.799 --> 00:06:18.079
As many as you want.

00:06:18.079 --> 00:06:20.640
We have a series of formatter functions.

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:23.779
They all begin with FNT underscore.

00:06:23.779 --> 00:06:26.880
And these are great for making the data appear as you want them to appear.

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:30.799
It's kind of like an Excel where you're selecting a bunch of cells and applying a format.

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:33.079
It's the same sort of idea here.

00:06:33.079 --> 00:06:37.040
I'll walk you through a few of these just to show you what they do.

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:38.320
Formatting numbers is really simple.

00:06:38.320 --> 00:06:39.320
Use format number.

00:06:39.320 --> 00:06:44.500
Here's a before and after sort of shot of, like, the data.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:45.640
So we have this column right here.

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:46.640
It's got some data.

00:06:46.640 --> 00:06:48.739
It's to three decimal places.

00:06:48.739 --> 00:06:50.519
And we can use format number.

00:06:50.519 --> 00:06:52.660
Just put in the argument decimals equals one.

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:53.660
And yeah.

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:54.660
We have it to one decimal place.

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:56.040
And even throws in a comma for you.

00:06:56.040 --> 00:07:00.040
Which you can disable as well.

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:03.079
So GT knows about currencies.

00:07:03.079 --> 00:07:04.239
And actually locales, too.

00:07:04.239 --> 00:07:05.239
It's crazy.

00:07:05.239 --> 00:07:06.799
So it can do all sorts of currencies.

00:07:06.799 --> 00:07:09.200
You just provide a currency code.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:10.200
Which is easy to look up.

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:13.279
And we actually have a function that gives you a table of currency codes.

00:07:13.279 --> 00:07:14.279
And yeah.

00:07:14.279 --> 00:07:15.279
Past use currency.

00:07:15.279 --> 00:07:16.279
Format currency.

00:07:16.279 --> 00:07:20.799
And then that before column becomes a set of currency code.

00:07:20.799 --> 00:07:23.679
A set of currencies right here.

00:07:23.679 --> 00:07:26.679
And the locale here just ensures that the formatting is correct for the locale here

00:07:26.679 --> 00:07:31.239
using French and France.

00:07:31.239 --> 00:07:33.839
So there may be some NAs in your data.

00:07:33.839 --> 00:07:36.420
And they appear in GT as NAs.

00:07:36.420 --> 00:07:37.420
Those can be replaced.

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:39.239
You just use format missing.

00:07:39.239 --> 00:07:40.239
Choose some replacement text.

00:07:40.239 --> 00:07:41.799
In the default case, we just use an em dash.

00:07:41.799 --> 00:07:43.519
And it looks pretty good in the presentation table.

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:50.000
But you can choose any sort of text that you want and target any sort of NAs that are applicable

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:51.000
for that text.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Okay.

