00:13:42.159 --> 00:13:44.919
It's a bit more complicated, because you're targeting potentially anywhere in the table

00:13:44.919 --> 00:13:46.159
to put a footnote.

00:13:46.159 --> 00:13:50.799
So we have this locations argument, and it takes a number of location helper functions.

00:13:50.799 --> 00:13:56.599
So we have cells underscore data, cells underscore column labels, title, all sorts of things

00:13:56.599 --> 00:13:57.599
like that.

00:13:57.599 --> 00:14:00.080
It just allows you to target where you want to put the footnote, and it attaches it to

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:01.080
the end of the text.

00:14:01.080 --> 00:14:04.440
So in this case, we're using cells data, because we want to target some data.

00:14:04.440 --> 00:14:08.840
And the interface is that we have columns and rows, and it's just like the formatters

00:14:08.840 --> 00:14:09.840
in this case.

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:12.840
We can provide an expression, provide some column name.

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:17.320
And so it's gonna attach to currencies where the value is less than 20.

00:14:17.320 --> 00:14:19.559
So just because these are formatted doesn't mean the value is still not there.

00:14:19.919 --> 00:14:24.520
It's an immutable table inside the actual object, so we can still use the values.

00:14:24.520 --> 00:14:28.000
So anything less than 20, we'll get this footnote.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:29.520
